def plot_it(y, sr):
    '''Plots the acoustic wave of a given samplerate'''
    times = np.arange(len(y))
    times = (times / sr) * 1000
    plt.plot(times, frag)
    
def fades(sig, sr=22050, time=50, curve=None, sides='both'):
    '''Returns a signal with fade-ins and fade-outs.'''

    # calculate fade times in samples
    f_time = int(sr * (time / 1000))
    
    # make fade-in and fade-out signals
    fi = np.linspace(0, 1, f_time)
    fo = np.linspace(1, 0, f_time)
    
    # apply curve
    if curve != None:
        fi = fi ** curve
        fo = fo ** curve
        
    # cut the signal and apply fades
    start = sig[:f_time] * fi
    body = sig[f_time:-f_time]
    end = sig[-f_time:] * fo
    
    # join and return
    return np.concatenate((start, body, end))

Przykłady audio¶

Przykład 1¶

Usyszysz trzy pary tonw, rnice si midzy sob pod wzgldem czstotliwoci o 10Hz. Dla pierwszej pary (200Hz i 210Hz) bardzo atwo jest usysze rnic. Dla drugiej pary (1000Hz i 1010Hz) rnic wychwyci wprawne ucho. Dla trzeciej pary (8000Hz i 8010Hz) rnica jest niesyszalna. Przykad ten ilustruje konsekwencje wynikajce z rozszerzania si szerokoci filtrw limakowych w miar wzrostu czstotliwoci.

In [3]:
sr = 22050

elements = (
    fades(librosa.core.tone(200, duration=1) * 0.5),
    np.zeros(1000),
    fades(librosa.core.tone(210, duration=1) * 0.5),
    np.zeros(22050),
    fades(librosa.core.tone(1000, duration=1) * 0.5),
    np.zeros(1000),
    fades(librosa.core.tone(1010, duration=1) * 0.5),
    np.zeros(22050),
    fades(librosa.core.tone(8000, duration=1) * 0.5),
    np.zeros(1000),
    fades(librosa.core.tone(8010, duration=1) * 0.5),
    np.zeros(1000)
    )

tone = np.concatenate(elements)

ipd.Audio(tone, rate=sr)

In [14]:
# Make a new figure
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))

# subfigure one
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)

# Let's make and display a mel-scaled power (energy-squared) spectrogram
S = librosa.feature.melspectrogram(dog, sr=sr, n_mels=128)

# Convert to log scale (dB). We'll use the peak power (max) as reference.
log_S = librosa.power_to_db(S, ref=np.max)


# Display the spectrogram on a mel scale
# sample rate and hop length parameters are used to render the time axis
librosa.display.specshow(log_S, sr=sr, x_axis='time', y_axis='mel')

# X axis label
plt.xlabel('Czas (sek)')

# Put a descriptive title on the plot
plt.title('Spektrogramy')

# draw a color bar
plt.colorbar(format='%+02.0f dB')


# subfigure two
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)

# Let's make and display a mel-scaled power (energy-squared) spectrogram
S = librosa.feature.melspectrogram(gtr, sr=sr, n_mels=128)

# Convert to log scale (dB). We'll use the peak power (max) as reference.
log_S = librosa.power_to_db(S, ref=np.max)

# Display the spectrogram on a mel scale
# sample rate and hop length parameters are used to render the time axis
librosa.display.specshow(log_S, sr=sr, x_axis='time', y_axis='mel')

# X axis label
plt.xlabel('Czas (sek)')

# draw a color bar
plt.colorbar(format='%+02.0f dB')

# Make the figure layout compact
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('spectro.png', dpi=150)
plt.show()

from scipy.signal import hilbert
analytic_signal = hilbert(dog)
dog_envelope = np.abs(analytic_signal)
analytic_signal = hilbert(gtr)
gtr_envelope = np.abs(analytic_signal)
